{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:20:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:20:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17331"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.85,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69922"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10021"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6798"},{"type":"tags","id":"7569"},{"type":"tags","id":"8644"},{"type":"tags","id":"8645"},{"type":"tags","id":"9846"},{"type":"tags","id":"9892"},{"type":"tags","id":"11232"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23469"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69922"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe alveoli are the primary sites of gas exchange in the lungs. Their structure is specially adapted to facilitate efficient oxygen and carbon dioxide transfer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular composition of alveolar walls?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Only type I cells are present","Equal numbers of type I and type II cells","Type I cells cover 95% and type II cells cover 5% of surface area","Only type II cells are present","Type I cells cover 5% and type II cells cover 95% of surface area"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe alveolar wall consists primarily of \u003Cstrong\u003Etype I cells covering 95% and type II cells covering 5% of the surface area\u003C/strong\u003E. Type I cells are extremely thin and flat, making them ideal for gas exchange. Type II cells are more cuboidal and produce surfactant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType I cells cover 5% and type II cells cover 95% of surface area\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the reverse of the correct distribution\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual numbers of type I and type II cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While the numbers may be similar, the surface area distribution is highly unequal to optimize gas exchange\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly type I cells are present\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II cells are essential for surfactant production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly type II cells are present\u003C/strong\u003E - Type I cells are crucial for gas exchange\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETogether with the capillary endothelium and basement membrane, these cells form the blood-air barrier. Type II cells can also serve as progenitor cells, differentiating into type I cells when needed for repair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alveolar type I cells cover 95% of the alveolar surface area and are specialized for gas exchange","Alveolar type II cells produce surfactant and can differentiate into type I cells when needed","The blood-air barrier consists of the alveolar epithelium, basement membrane, and capillary endothelium"],"references":["Netter FH (Frank H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy\u202f: Classic Regional Approach. Eighth edition. (Neumann PE, Tubbs RS, Brueckner JK, et al., eds.). Elsevier; 2022.","Beachey W. Respiratory Care Anatomy and Physiology: Foundations for Clinical Practice. Fifth Edition. Elsevier; 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17331"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T01:55:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T01:57:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10021"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69922"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/